# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fire-retardant-fabric
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/area-of-refuge] An **area of refuge** or **safe room** is a place in a building designed to hold occupants during a fire or other emergency when evacuation may not be safe or possible.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/area-of-refuge] Occupants can wait there until rescued or relieved by firefighters.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/area-of-refuge] In some instances, an area of refuge or refuge area may refer to a designated space in a multi-unit residential building that can provide relief from unsafe or uncomfortable conditions in individual units.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/area-of-refuge] An area of refuge is typically supplied with a steady supply of fresh or filtered outside air.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/area-of-refuge] A two way communication system is provided on each floor above or below the main floor.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/area-of-refuge] A call box is required in each area of refuge, which can call into a central location called a base station.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/area-of-refuge] If the station is not attended 24 hours a day, the call must automatically call to an outside location and have two-way voice person to person communication capabilities.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/area-of-refuge] Such locations are usually required to be bounded by fire-resistant walls and floors.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/area-of-refuge] In the context of climate change, where older buildings may not be designed for changing climate conditions, refuge spaces are sometimes discussed in terms of providing communal areas in multi-unit buildings for when temperature and air quality is not safe or comfortable in individual units.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/arthur-b-guise-medal] Guise Medal** was established in 1983 and has been awarded annually starting in 1985 by the Society of Fire Protection Engineers.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/arthur-b-guise-medal] Named in memory of Arthur Guise, an engineer who developed dry chemicals as fire extinguishing agents, it recognizes eminent achievement in the advancement of the science and technology of fire protection engineering.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] An **aspirating smoke detector** (**ASD**) is a system used in active fire protection, consisting of a central detection unit which draws air through a network of pipes to detect smoke.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] The sampling chamber is based on a nephelometer that detects the presence of smoke particles suspended in air by detecting the light scattered by them in the chamber.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs can typically detect smoke before it is visible to the naked eye.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] In most cases aspirating smoke detectors require a fan unit to draw in a sample of air from the protected area through its network of pipes.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1970 the Australian Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO) used a nephelometer to carry out research into forest fires.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] Subsequently, the Australian Postmaster-General's Department engaged the CSIRO to investigate technologies that could prevent service interruption due to fire.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] After selecting a sample site to carry out research, the CSIRO suggested that the nephelometer should be used as the benchmark for the APO fire tests.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] This was installed to monitor smoke levels within the return-air ducts of the mechanical ventilation system, utilising a chart-recorder output display.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] At the conclusion of several weeks of testing, it was discovered that there no commercially available fire detection technology suitable for preventing damage to telephone equipment.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] One technology that did show great promise however was the nephelometer itself.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1979, Xtralis, then IEI Pty Ltd., produced and sold an air sampling device they called VESDA (Very Early Smoke Detection Apparatus).
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] The company redesigned the detector in 1982 to provide the reliability, features, size and reduced cost for export markets.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems have gained popularity due to their ability to sense smoke long before a catastrophic incident.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD design corrects shortcomings of conventional smoke detectors by using a sampling pipe with multiple holes.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] The air samples are captured and filtered, removing any contaminants or dust to avoid false alarms and then processed by a centralized, highly sensitive laser detection unit.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] If smoke is detected, the systems alarm is triggered, and signals are then processed through centralized monitoring stations within a few seconds.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] Unlike passive smoke detection systems, including spot detectors, ASD systems actively draw smoke to the detector through bore holes within a piping system that runs throughout the protected area.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] Furthermore, ASD systems incorporate integrity monitoring to ensure an alert is raised at any time the ASD's ability to detect smoke is compromised.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] This is not the case with passive devices that are generally only electrically monitored with no ability to determine if smoke can actually reach the detection element.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems incorporate more than one level of alarm.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] This allows an ASD system to provide very early warning of an event, prompting investigation at the earliest smouldering stage of a fire when it is easily addressed.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] Other alarm levels may be configured to provide fire alarm inputs to fire systems as well as releasing suppression systems.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD alarm sensitivities are configurable and can be programmed to levels ranging from thousands of times more sensitive than a conventional detector, to much less sensitive.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] The detectors work best in non-volatile environments.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] They can also be used in computer cabinets to alert users to the overheating of computer cables or individual computer components.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs are suitable for environments where a highly sensitive rapid smoke detection capability is required.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] This makes them suitable in clean rooms; areas which contain goods easily damaged by fire, such as tobacco, electronic rooms and highly flammable liquid and gases.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] Often, normal point detectors will recognise the danger too late, as smoke often does not reach the ceiling quickly enough for a fire to be detected in a timely fashion.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] As they can be easily hidden, pipe networks are suitable in environments where point detectors can be considered aesthetically displeasing, such as offices, apartments and hotel rooms.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] This factor also makes them suitable in locations where point detectors can be easily tampered with, such as in correctional facilities.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] Despite their high sensitivity ASDs can be used in dusty or dirty environments as long as correct design, installation and maintenance processes are followed.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/aspirating-smoke-detector] Most ASD products can accommodate a broad range of environments and applications – from both confined and open spaces to the cleanest or dirtiest environment, including telecomm, control rooms, waste treatment, mining and more.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Today there are numerous types of automatic fire suppression systems and standards for each one.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Systems are as diverse as the many applications.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] In general, however, automatic fire suppression systems fall into two categories: *engineered* and *pre-engineered* systems.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] By definition, an automatic fire suppression system can operate without human intervention.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] To do so it must possess a means of detection, actuation and delivery.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] In many systems, detection is accomplished by mechanical or electrical means.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Mechanical detection uses fusible-link or thermo-bulb detectors.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] These detectors are designed to separate at a specific temperature and release tension on a release mechanism.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Electrical detection uses heat detectors equipped with self-restoring, normally-open contacts which close when a predetermined temperature is reached.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Remote and local manual operation is also possible.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Actuation usually involves either a pressurized fluid and a release valve, or in some cases an electric pump.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Delivery is accomplished by means of piping and nozzles.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Nozzle design is specific to the agent used and coverage desired.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Water is the most prevalent fire suppression agent in use worldwide.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] However, the use of water does have some limitations, which can range from inadequate supplies (particularly in less developed regions) to operations and processes which are highly susceptible to water damage.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] In some cases, certain contents or processes (such as water-reactive chemicals or metals, molten materials, etc.) are truly incompatible with water; water discharge could lead to explosion.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Despite their effectiveness, chemical fire extinguishing agents are not without disadvantages.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] In the early 20th century, carbon tetrachloride was extensively used as a dry cleaning solvent, a refrigerant and as a fire extinguishing agent.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] In time, it was found carbon tetrachloride could lead to severe health effects.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] From the mid-1960s Halon 1301 was the industry standard for protecting high-value assets from the threat of fire.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Halon 1301 had many benefits as a fire suppression agent; it is fast-acting, safe for assets and required minimal storage space.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Halon 1301's major drawbacks are that it depletes atmospheric ozone and is potentially harmful to humans.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Since 1987, some 191 nations have signed The Montreal Protocol on Substances That Deplete the Ozone Layer.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] The Protocol is an international treaty designed to protect the ozone layer by phasing out the production of a number of substances believed to be responsible for ozone depletion.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Among these were halogenated hydrocarbons often used in fire suppression.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] As a result, manufacturers have focused on alternatives to Halon 1301 and Halon 1211 (halogenated hydrocarbons).
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] A number of countries have also taken steps to mandate the removal of installed Halon systems.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Most notably these include Germany and Australia, the first two countries in the world to require this action.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] In both of these countries complete removal of installed Halon systems has been completed except for a very few essential-use applications.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] The European Union is currently undergoing a similar mandated removal of installed Halon systems.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] The first fire extinguisher patent was issued to Alanson Crane of Virginia on Feb.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] The first fire sprinkler system was patented by H.W.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] But the first practical automatic sprinkler system was invented in 1874 by Henry S.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] He installed the system in a piano factory he owned.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Since the early 1990s manufacturers have successfully developed safe and effective Halon alternatives.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] These include DuPont's FM-200, American Pacific's Halotron, FirePro's FPC Compound, Plumis’ Automist and 3M's Novec 1230 Fire Protection Fluid.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Generally, the Halon replacement agents available today fall into two broad categories, in-kind (gaseous extinguishing agents) or not in-kind (alternative technologies).
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] In-kind gaseous agents generally fall into two further categories, halocarbons and inert gases.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/automatic-fire-suppression] Not in-kind alternatives include such options as water mist or the use of early warning smoke detection systems.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] A **backdraft** (North American English), **backdraught** (British English) or **smoke explosion** is the abrupt burning of superheated gases in a fire caused when oxygen rapidly enters a hot, oxygen-depleted environment; for example, when a window or door to an enclosed space is opened or broken.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] Backdrafts are typically seen as a blast of smoke and/or flame out of an opening of a building.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] Backdrafts present a serious threat to firefighters.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] There is some debate concerning whether backdrafts should be considered a type of flashover.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] When material is heated enough, it begins to break down into smaller compounds, including flammable or even explosive gas, typically hydrocarbons.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] This is called pyrolysis, and does not require oxygen.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] If oxygen is also provided, then the hydrocarbons can combust, starting a fire.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] If material undergoing pyrolysis is later given sufficient oxygen, the hydrocarbons will ignite and, therefore, combustion takes place.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] A backdraft can occur when a compartment fire has little or no ventilation.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] Due to this, little or no oxygen can flow into the compartment.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] Then, because fires reduce oxygen, the oxygen concentration decreases.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] When the oxygen concentration becomes too low to support combustion, some or all of the combustion switches to pyrolysis.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] Nonetheless, the hydrocarbons and smoke (primarily particulate matter) remain at a temperature hot enough to auto-ignite.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] The colour and movement of smoke is used by firefighters to infer fire conditions, including the risk of backdraft.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] This is an indication that the room lacks enough oxygen to permit oxidation of the soot particles.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] Firefighters often look to see if there is soot on the inside of windows and in any cracks in the window (caused e.g. by the heat).
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] The windows may also have a slight vibration due to varying pressure within the compartment due to intermittent combustion.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] If firefighters discover a room sucking air into itself, for example through a crack, they generally evacuate immediately, because this is a strong indication that a backdraft is imminent.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] Due to pressure differences, puffs of smoke are sometimes drawn back into the enclosed space from which they emanated, which is how the term *backdraft* originated.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] Backdrafts are very dangerous, often surprising even experienced firefighters.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] The most common tactic used by firefighters to defuse a potential backdraft is to ventilate a room from its highest point, allowing the heat and smoke to escape without igniting.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] In common usage, the term flashover describes the near-simultaneous ignition of material caused by heat attaining the autoignition temperature of the combustible material and gases in an enclosure.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] Flashovers according to this narrower definition, i.e. those caused by rising temperatures, would not be considered backdrafts since backdrafts are caused by the introduction of oxygen into an enclosed space with conditions already suitable for ignition, and are thus caused by chemical change.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] Backdrafts were publicized by the 1991 movie *Backdraft*, in which a serial arsonist in Chicago uses them as a means of assassinating conspirators in a scam.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] In the film adaptation of Stephen King's *1408*, the protagonist Mike Enslin induces one as a last-ditch effort to kill the room.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] The term is also used and is the title of a scene in the 2012 video game *Root Double: Before Crime * After Days*.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/backdraft] In the second book of the light novel series Imperial Reincarnation: I Came, I Saw, I Survived, the character Carmine uses a magically produced backdraft to defend himself against an assassination attempt.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] The **British Standards Institution** (**BSI**) is the national standards body of the United Kingdom.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] BSI produces technical standards on a wide range of products and services and also supplies standards certification services for business and personnel.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] BSI was founded as the Engineering Standards Committee in London in 1901.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] It subsequently extended its standardization work and became the British Engineering Standards Association in 1918, adopting the name British Standards Institution in 1931 after receiving a Royal Charter in 1929.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] In 1998, a revision of the Charter enabled the organization to diversify and acquire other businesses, and the trading name was changed to BSI Group.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] The Group now operates in 195 countries.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] The core business remains standards and standards related services, although the majority of the Group's revenue comes from management systems assessment and certification work.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] In 2021, BSI appointed its first female chief executive officer, Susan Taylor Martin.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] BSI produces British Standards, and, as the UK's National Standards Body, is also responsible for the UK publication, in English, of international and European standards.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] BSI is obliged to adopt and publish all European Standards as identical British Standards (prefixed BS EN) and to withdraw pre-existing British Standards that are in conflict.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] However, it has the option to adopt and publish international standards (prefixed BS ISO or BS IEC).
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] In response to commercial demands, BSI also produces commissioned standards products such as Publicly Available Specifications (PASs), Private Standards and Business Information Publications.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] These products are commissioned by individual organizations and trade associations to meet their needs for standardized specifications, guidelines, codes of practice etc.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] Because they are not subject to the same consultation and consensus requirements as formal standards, the lead time is shorter.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] BSI also publishes standards-related books, CD-ROMs, subscription and web-based products as well as providing training on standards-related issues.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] With 80,000 clients, BSI is one of the world's largest certification bodies.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] It audits and provides certification to companies worldwide who implement management systems standards.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] BSI also runs training courses that cover the implementation and auditing requirements of national and international management systems standards.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] BSI's best known product in the UK is the Kitemark, a registered certification mark first used in 1903.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] The Kitemark – which is recognized by 82% of UK adults – signifies products or services which have been assessed and tested as meeting the requirements of the related specification or standard within a Kitemark scheme.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] BSI also conducts testing of products for a range of certifications, including for CE marking.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] CE marking must be applied to a wide range of products intended for sale in the European Economic Area.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] Frequently, manufacturers or importers need a third-party certification of their product from an accredited or 'Notified' body.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] BSI holds Notified Body status for 15 EU Directives, including construction products, marine equipment, pressurized equipment and personal protective equipment.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] BSI also conducts testing for manufacturers developing new products and has facilities to test across a wide range of sectors, including construction, fire safety, electrical and electronic and engineering products.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] BSI provides regulatory and quality management reviews and product certification for medical device manufacturers in the Worldwide.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] It is the market leader in the US, the world's biggest healthcare market.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] In 2021, BSI Group, with support from the Construction Products Association, led the development of a product identification and traceability system known as *BSI Identify*.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] The initiative responded to recommendations made by Dame Judith Hackitt following her review of building safety, which called for wider adoption of permanent product marking and consistent labelling systems to improve traceability across the built environment sector.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] BSI Identify uses new Digital Object Identifier (DOI) technology "to deliver a unique, constant, and interoperable identifier", known as a BSI UPIN, "which can be assigned to products to help UK manufacturers to directly manage information about their products in the supply chain".
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] The aim of the BSI Identify programme is that "wherever you are with [a] product, you can take a snapshot of the QR code with your mobile device, and it will immediately take you to the product technical data sheet.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/bsi-group] The BSI coat of arms was granted by the College of Arms in 1951.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] They are used in a wide variety of areas that require the attributes of being retardant to flames, including protective clothing, curtains, household upholstery, and other industrial items.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] To ensure these fabrics maintain a quality of effectiveness, they must meet a very strict set of safety standards, such as NFPA 701 (North America) and EN 13501 (Europe).
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] These standards can be maintained through the use of selective materials and specialized treatments that can reduce flammability greatly and delay combustion.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] The term *fire retardant* or *flame retardant* applies to a chemical substance that is or can be applied or treated to materials in order to prevent the start of or slow the growth of fire.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] The tests used specified in building codes, such as NFPA 701, are more correctly *flame resistance* tests, which test a fabric's ability to resist ignition with the flame size and duration in the test conditions.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] The result is a comparative test, which provides a measure of the material's resistance to propagating combustion caused by small scale ignition sources.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] However, these tests do not predict the burning characteristics of full scale hazards.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] In many cases, if exposed to a sufficiently large and sustained exposure fire, the fire-retardant fabrics will burn vigorously.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] Polyester is inherently flame retardant, and therefore doesn't flare up when applied to various tests.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] Any amount of heat delivered within a long enough time interval will have no impact on the fabrics' integrity while a limited amount of heat delivered within short enough time interval may ignite or melt the fabric.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] Inherently flame-retardant fabrics are certified in the United Kingdom by various British Standards.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] Fire-retardant fabrics sold in the UK for use as curtains must abide by BS 5867 Part 2 B & C, a British Standard.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] Other relevant UK standards include BS 5815-1 2005, BS 7175, Crib 5, IMO A563 and NFPA 701.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] These are treated in chemicals to increase its ability to resist fire and combusting easily.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] Importantly, treated fabrics may lose their effectiveness of flame retardancy over time or if the curtains are exposed to outside conditions.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] Affected items could require retreatment or replacement.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] Fabric flammability is an important textile issue, especially for stage drapery that will be used in a public space such as a school, theatre or special event venue.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] In the United States, Federal regulations require that drapery fabrics used in such spaces be certified as flame or fire-retardant.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] For draperies and other fabrics used in public places, this is known as the NFPA 701 Test, which follows standards developed by the National Fire Protection Association (NFPA).
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] Although all fabrics will burn, some are naturally more resistant to fire than others.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] Those that are more flammable can have their fire resistance drastically improved by treatment with fire-retardant chemicals.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] Inherently flame-retardant fabrics such as certain brand polyesters are commonly used for flame retardant curtain fabrics.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] Benefits of these fabrics help maintain the fire-resistant properties over time without the need to retreat the fabric.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] They are built to work as durable working fabrics that can be cleaned repeatedly and retain the properties that make it fire-resistant.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] Fire-retardant fabrics are normally treated to different British Standards; normally this depends on the end usage of the fabrics.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] The M1 standard is a European standard that is widely used in Europe only.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] In construction, "M1" is part of a bigger classification system that France and Finland primarily use, but is used across the country.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] This relates to the reaction that materials have when ignited, i.e. insulation, wall panels, textiles, furniture, etc.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] The classification system has 5 levels from M0-Non-combustible, to M4-Easily flammable where the materials are tested for heat release, production of smoke, flame spread rate, and ignitability.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] UK fire officers are reluctant to accept M1 certification, as they prefer BS certificates due to the detail that the BS certifications go into, and lean more into legal, insurance, and safety measures in UK businesses.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] When a fabric is designated as *inherently fire-retardant*, *permanently fire-retardant*, or *durably fire-retardant*, the flame retardancy will last for the life of the fabric as it has been woven into the fabric fiber itself.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] The drapery can be laundered or dry-cleaned as recommended by the drapery manufacturer.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] In the case of fabrics that are designated as *fire-retardant*, and that have been topically treated with chemicals, the flame retardancy of the fabric will dissipate over time, particularly with repeated cleaning.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] As these chemicals are soluble in liquids, either water or dry cleaning fluid, these fabrics must be dry-cleaned with a non-liquid cleaning agent.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] The flame retardants work by coating the flammable fabrics with a mineral based barrier, preventing fire from reaching the fibers.
[src:fire-retardant-fabric/fire-retardant-fabric] It is recommended that topically treated drapery be re-tested for fire-retardancy on an annual basis and re-treated by a qualified professional as needed.
